          "title": "The abandoned Egyptian — providence as an unexpected guide",
          "body": "Between the divine command and the military victory, the narrator inserts what might seem like a digression: an Egyptian slave found half-dead in a field, given bread, water, figs, and raisins by David's men, and slowly revived over three days (30:11-12). The detail is far from incidental. This abandoned servant of an Amalekite becomes the guide who leads David to the Amalekite camp (30:15-16). Providence does not operate here through dramatic vision or angelic intervention — it operates through a sick man left behind by a cruel master, met by a compassionate leader who stops to feed him. David's men did not have to stop. They were in urgent pursuit. The decision to restore this man's strength is an act of hesed — covenant kindness — extended to an outsider. And that act of kindness returns to David as military intelligence. Chuck Swindoll, in his study of David's life, notes that the Egyptian episode reveals something essential about David's character: he does not treat people instrumentally even when he could. He feeds first and inquires second (30:11, then 30:13). The providential structure of the chapter rewards that posture: God supplies what David needs through the very person David stops to help."
