          "title": "Total recovery — the faithfulness of God's promise",
          "body": "Verse 8 promised 'you will surely rescue all.' Verse 19 delivers: 'nothing of theirs was missing, whether small or great, sons or daughters, spoil or anything that they had taken for themselves; David brought it all back.' The parallel between promise and fulfillment is exact and deliberate. The narrator holds the two verses together so that the reader cannot miss the correspondence — God said 'all,' and David recovered 'all.' The battle itself (30:17) is dispatched in a single verse: David slaughters from twilight to evening the next day, with four hundred camel-riders the only escapees. The brevity of the battle description and the fullness of the recovery description shows where the narrator's interest lies — not in military strategy but in the precision of divine faithfulness. This is the Old Testament pattern of holy war: when Israel fights at God's explicit command and with God's declared promise, the outcome is not in doubt. The drama is not 'will David win?' but 'will God's word prove true?' — and the answer is 'nothing was missing.'"
