          "title": "The statute of equal shares — theology turned into law",
          "body": "The wicked men's proposal in verse 22 — send the exhausted home with only their families, no spoil — is the chapter's internal crisis. It is also the chapter's sharpest test of what kind of kingdom David will build. David's answer is theological before it is political: 'with what the LORD has given us' (30:23). He does not argue military logic or human merit. He argues divine origin: because the victory is Yahweh's gift, not the fighters' achievement, no one has the standing to withhold it from a brother. The statute he establishes — equal shares for fighter and rear-guard alike — is directly analogous to what Calvin called the 'common equity' of biblical law: the substance is moral and permanent even if the form is situational. Peter Davids, commenting on the parallel in James 2 (favoritism among believers), notes the same logic: those who have received grace from God cannot distribute it according to human merit-rankings. David's statute becomes Israel's law and echoes forward into the New Testament theology of the body of Christ, where every member's contribution is necessary and honorable (1 Corinthians 12:22-26)."
